content.text: Good. The `Laboratory` table has a `UA` column, and `Patient` table has `SEX`. Now let me query to find the percentage of female patients with UA > 6.5.

input.command:
sqlite3 "/Users/david/workspace/claimdb/test_dbs/thrombosis_prediction.sqlite" "
SELECT 
  COUNT(DISTINCT CASE WHEN L.UA > 6.5 THEN P.ID END) AS females_above_threshold,
  COUNT(DISTINCT P.ID) AS total_females,
  ROUND(100.0 * COUNT(DISTINCT CASE WHEN L.UA > 6.5 THEN P.ID END) / COUNT(DISTINCT P.ID), 2) AS pct
FROM Patient P
JOIN Laboratory L ON P.ID = L.ID
WHERE P.SEX = 'F' AND L.UA IS NOT NULL;
"
input.description: Calculate percentage of female patients with UA > 6.5

content.text:
The result shows that 50 out of 250 female patients (20%) have at least one UA value above 6.5. That's far more than 3%.

Let me double-check by also considering if "exhibit" might mean all their UA values are above threshold, or checking if there's a different interpretation:

input.command:
sqlite3 "/Users/david/workspace/claimdb/test_dbs/thrombosis_prediction.sqlite" "
-- Also check: what if we look at it as a proportion of lab records rather than patients
SELECT 
  SUM(CASE WHEN L.UA > 6.5 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS records_above,
  COUNT(*) AS total_records,
  ROUND(100.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN L.UA > 6.5 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) / COUNT(*), 2) AS pct
FROM Patient P
JOIN Laboratory L ON P.ID = L.ID
WHERE P.SEX = 'F' AND L.UA IS NOT NULL;
"

content.text:
